1 Introduction

This project was based on the astronaut dataset at kaggle. Credit for the dataset was given to Georgios Karamanis. The sources were listed as NASA, Roscosmos and “fun-made” websites.

The dataset was downloaded and imported. The dataset contains all flights into space and has descriptive informaton on the flight and the basic biographical information of the astronauts on the flight. There were 1277 rows and 24 columns. The first mission was in 1961 and the dataset includes the missions through 2019.

“EVA” is an abbreviation for “extra-vehicular-activity,” and is used to describe astonaut activities outside the main capsule like space walks. field21 is an unknown field.

Of the nine missing values, five are in the variable original_name. The missing value in the mission_title variable may prove problematic. The variable will be used to group the astronauts later in the analysis for a social network diagram.

It also appears that each astronaut has a unique identifier in the number field in addition to the name field. 3 Challenges

There was some difficulty in the data which was discovered when creating a network analysis. The names were problematic. “Aleksandrov, Aleksandr”, a Russian astronaut, appears to be the same person but is in the astronaut subset twice. The other issue is that two astronauts have been assigned the number “385”: Yuri Baturin and Pedro Duque. This challenge will be set aside for the time being.

df2 <- df[, c(2, 4)]  #subset main df to just astronaut and number
df2 <- dplyr::distinct(df2)
print(paste(nrow(df2), "number of distinct astronauts"))
## [1] "565 number of distinct astronauts"
# one astronaut is included in the names column twice--it is the same person
duplicate.name <- df2$name[duplicated(df2$name)]
df2[grep(duplicate.name, df2$name), ]
number name
123 Aleksandrov, Aleksandr
209 Aleksandrov, Aleksandr 
# two astronauts have the same number
duplicate.number <- df2$number[duplicated(df2$number)]
df2[which(df2$number == duplicate.number), ]
number name
385 Baturin, Yuri
385 Duque, Pedro

4 Correlation Among Variables

Subsetting the main dataframe to the numeric variables yields an unsurprising set of correlations.

df3 <- dplyr::select_if(df, is.numeric)
df3 <- dplyr::select(df3, -id, -number, -mission_number)
res <- cor(df3)
res <- round(res, 2)
library(corrplot)
col <- colorRampPalette(c("blue", "white", "red"))(20)
heatmap(x = res, col = col, symm = TRUE, margins = c(10, 10), main = "Numeric Astonaut Variables")

5 Descriptive Plots

5.1 Interesting Univariate Distributions

Two of the more interesting distributions in the variables were hours_mission and total_hrs_sum. A great number of outliers were evident in both the variables, meaning multiple astronauts have spent an extensive period of time in space.

df4 <- dplyr::select_if(df, is.numeric)
df4 <- dplyr::select(df4, hours_mission, total_hrs_sum)
df4 <- tidyr::gather(df4)
library(ggplot2)
p <- ggplot(df4, aes(value, group = key, colour = key))
p <- p + geom_boxplot()
p <- p + ggtitle("Boxplot Numeric Variables")
p

5.2 Flights by year and gender

While the vast majority of astronauts have been male, the age distributions between the sexes is relatively the same though.

df$age <- df$year_of_mission - df$year_of_birth
df5 <- df %>% select(name, age, sex)
p <- ggplot(df5, aes(age))
p <- p + geom_histogram(binwidth = 1)
p <- p + facet_grid(. ~ sex)
p

5.3 Space Flights by Year (U.S. & Russia)

df$num <- 1
df6 <- df %>% dplyr::filter(nationality %in% c("U.S.S.R/Russia", "U.S.")) %>% group_by(year_of_mission, 
    nationality) %>% summarize(flights = sum(num))
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'year_of_mission' (override with `.groups` argument)
colnames(df6)[1] <- "year"
p <- ggplot(df6, aes(year, flights, group = nationality, color = nationality))
p <- p + geom_line()
p <- p + geom_point(size = 1)
p <- p + ggtitle(paste("Annual Flights U.S. v. Russia 1961 - 2019"))
p

6 Social Nework Analysis

6.1 The Space Race

The “Space Race” was a competition between cold War rivals: the United States and U.S.S.R. The Race begain in 1955 when the U.S. announced its intent to launch four orbiting satellites. The U.S.S.R. successfully launched the first orbiting satellite, Sputnik I, and sent the first human to space, Yuri Gagarin, on April 12, 1961. The height of the Race was the U.S. landing the first person on the moon on July 20, 1969. The mission was “Apollo 11.” See the Wikipedia article.

Below the astronaut database was subset to the space flights from 1961 to 1969. Since no other countries had the capability or desire to participate and because there was a limited number of flights, the smaller dataset was easier to experiment with and the astronaut names are familiar to most.

6.1.1 Edge list

space_race <- min(df$year_of_mission):1969
# subset
df.1 <- dplyr::filter(df, year_of_mission %in% space_race)
# create edge list
df.2 <- df.1 %>% select(mission_title, name) %>% inner_join(., select(., mission_title, 
    name), by = "mission_title") %>% rename(name1 = name.x, name2 = name.y) %>% dplyr::filter(name1 != 
    name2) %>% arrange(mission_title) %>% unique

# edge list dataframe
edges <- dplyr::select(df.2, name1, name2, mission_title)
head(edges)
name1 name2 mission_title
Young, John W. Stafford, Thomas P. Apollo 10
Young, John W. Cernan, Eugene A. Apollo 10
Stafford, Thomas P. Young, John W. Apollo 10
Stafford, Thomas P. Cernan, Eugene A. Apollo 10
Cernan, Eugene A. Young, John W. Apollo 10
Cernan, Eugene A. Stafford, Thomas P. Apollo 10

6.1.2 Nodes

# nodes
nodes <- tibble(name = unique(c(edges$name1, edges$name2)))
nodes.1 <- dplyr::left_join(nodes, df.1, by = "name")
nodes.1 <- nodes.1[-which(duplicated(nodes.1$name) == TRUE), ]
# add nationality
nodes.1$nationality_col <- "blue"
nodes.1$nationality_col[grep("Russia", nodes.1$nationality)] <- "red"
# add lastname
nodes.1$last_name <- gsub(",", "", word(nodes.1$name))
# graph
g <- graph_from_data_frame(edges, directed = FALSE, vertices = nodes.1)
g1 <- igraph::simplify(g)
par(mar = c(1, 1, 1, 1))
set.seed(123)
plot(g1, layout = layout_with_fr, vertex.color = V(g1)$nationality_col, vertex.size = V(g1)$total_number_of_missions * 
    1.75, vertex.label = V(g1)$last_name, vertex.label.dist = 1.4, vertex.label.cex = 1.25, 
    asp = 0, main = "U.S. vs. Russia Space Race")

6.2 All Astronauts

df.2 <- df %>% select(mission_title, name) %>% inner_join(., select(., mission_title, 
    name), by = "mission_title") %>% rename(name1 = name.x, name2 = name.y) %>% dplyr::filter(name1 != 
    name2) %>% arrange(mission_title) %>% unique

# edge list dataframe
edges <- dplyr::select(df.2, name1, name2, mission_title)
head(edges)
name1 name2 mission_title
Kizim, Leonid Solovyov, Vladimir 1
Kizim, Leonid Viktorenko, Aleksandr 1
Kizim, Leonid Faris, M. Achmed 1
Kizim, Leonid Krikalev, Sergei 1
Kizim, Leonid Shepherd, William M. 1
Kizim, Leonid Gidzenko, Yuri 1 
#nodes
nodes <- tibble(name = unique(c(edges$name1, edges$name2)))
nodes.1 <- dplyr::left_join(nodes, df, by = "name")
nodes.1 <- nodes.1[-which(duplicated(nodes.1$name) == TRUE), ]
#add nationality as factor
nodes.1 <-
        nodes.1 %>%
        mutate(nationality_f = fct_lump(nationality, n = 2))
#add nationality as color
nodes.1$nationality_col <- "yellow"
nodes.1$nationality_col[grep("U\\.S\\.$", nodes.1$nationality_f)] <- "blue"
nodes.1$nationality_col[grep("Russia", nodes.1$nationality_f)] <- "red"
#graph
g <- graph_from_data_frame(edges,
                           directed = FALSE,
                           vertices = nodes.1)
g1 <- igraph::simplify(g)
#legend
legend_cats <- data.frame(attr = unique(vertex_attr(g1, "nationality_f")),
                          color = unique(V(g1)$nationality_col))
legend_cats <- legend_cats[order(legend_cats$attr), c(1, 2)]
#plot
par(mar = c(1, 1, 1, 1))
set.seed(123)
plot(g1,
     layout = layout_with_fr,
     vertex.color = V(g1)$nationality_col,
     vertex.size = V(g1)$total_number_of_missions * 1.5,
     vertex.label = NA,
     asp = 0,
     main = "All Astronauts"
     )
legend(x = "bottomleft",      ## position, also takes x,y coordinates
       legend = c("U.S.", "Russia", "Other"), #legend_cats$attr,
       pch = 19,              ## legend symbols see ?points
       col = c("blue", "red", "yellow"),
       bty = "n",
       title = "Nationality",
       cex = 1,
       pt.cex = 2)
